In this struggle to defend the rights of the most vulnerable Americans in our midst, Montana becomes the second state this year to actually say, in one of the two legislative houses, that people of all ages deserve equal protection under the law. </font></strong><a target="_blank" href="http://ss.all.org/link.php?M=17565&amp;N=24&amp;L=179&amp;F=H"><strong><font size="3">North Dakota</font></strong></a><strong><font size="3"> became the first state just a week ago. There are, in addition, </font></strong><a target="_blank" href="http://ss.all.org/link.php?M=17565&amp;N=24&amp;L=172&amp;F=H"><strong><font size="3">five additional states</font></strong></a><strong><font size="3">&#160;where measures are being pursued as I write, and even more taking the entire question into serious consideration.<br /><br />
